<Author>Niamh12345
<Content>Good value but won't go back. My partner, 12 year old son  I stayed here for three nights (after staying in Gerona for a couple of nights). The hotes is very near the Sants train station, which was handy, but complicated traffic systems meant that what would be a short walk was a much longer drive.the hotel is situated in a fairly working-class residential area close to the Parallel street. Evening walking in the area felt slightly scary.The entrance lobby to the hotel is huge, with a real 5 star appearance. There is a tiny gift shop which is actually not too bad for last minute trinkets etc, though the very nice sales assistant took absolutely ages rummaging around for gift wrap to wrap each individual gift; nice touch but too too slow.The check in/out was slow, with very impersonal  uninterested staff. Lifts up to the room were a little slow,  the room we had (supposedly a slight upgrade from standard) was at the end of very long corridors. The room was very spacious, as advertised. The room had 2 queen size beds, which posed a bit of a problem. When I mentioned this to reception they seemed unwilling to do anything for us, though I did not push the issue. A queen size bed (about 4 foot wide I think) isn't big enough for my partner  I to sleep in comfortably, being used to standard double at least (4 foot 6 inches) or our own king size (5 foot wide). The other bed was for my son. So over the three nights we experimented with the format. Overall, though the beds were individually very comfortable, this was not satisfactory.The Bathroom, and indeed the hotel overall, looked like it had been built/designed in the 70's as a 5* luxury hotel, but now although not too shabby it does feel a little dated. The shower was merely satisfactory. The toiletries were ok. The minibar was full of the usual highly priced items which I refuse to purchase. There was a bottle of water (bizarrely, from Norway) on the bedside locker, looked more like a bottle of aftershave. This had a price sticker on it of 2.80 Euro. The chambermaids were a little too enthusiastic about arriving early, and knocked several times before we had gone out of the room for the day. Also, during our three days there we had two separate incidents of staff walking in unannounced while we were in the room.Despite the mini hallway entry to the room with a second door, the carpeted coridor seemed to produce a lot of noisy people  staff banging doors etc.We tried out the pool on one occasion. Tthis is in the hotel but is part of a separate gym which is open to the public members. The pool looked like any municipal pool, but was fine; no-one but us in it at the time.We didn't eat in the hotel at all, but there was a nice enough restaurant about 20 yards from the hotel front door. I can't remember the name of it, but beside it was a fairly expensive fish restaurant that looked great but was full when we tried to eat there.Checking out was painfully slow, but we were able to leave our bags in the storage facility while we did some more sightseeing, we collected our luggage later (had to queue again)  asked the porter to get us a taxi. This involved him standing out in the street trying to see if he could hail one, which took a good 5 minutes  we could have probably done this ourselves.Overall it was comfortable but not fantastic. 
